Such extraneae personae had always been able to retain for a man a possession which he bad validly got for himself : and it would seem that soon after the establishment of the empire (Dig. 41. 2. 51) it was attempted by an extension of the principle to break down the old rule as to the original acquisition of possession, and thus to get over the necessity of a double traditio. Labeo seems by implication (Dig. loc. cit.) to have favoured the proposed inno- vation, which was also approved by Javoleuus. Neratius, writing under Trajan, says โper procuratorem possessionem adipisci nos iamsere con- venit' Dig. 41. 3. 41: Gaius (ii. 95) refers to the controversy as still , unsettled: but Paulus (seut. rec 5. 2. 2), Ulpian (Dig. 41. r. 20. 2), and Modestinus (ib. 53), assert the new doctrine as though in their day it was completely and universally recognised. Thus the constitution of Severus (Cod 7. 32. 1)alluded to in the text did not make new law, but was merely a statutory confirmation of a principle already sufficiently established by juristic consensus, as indeed its terms themselves allow.
